To solve this, we first find the vectors corresponding to two sides of the triangle.
\begin{align*} {\bf v}_1 &= \vec{AB} = \begin{pmatrix} 0-(-1) \\ 7-6 \\ 10-6 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \\ {\bf v}_2 &= \vec{AC} = \begin{pmatrix} 0-(-4) \\ 7-9 \\ 10-6 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}
Next, we calculate the vector $${\bf v}_3 = {\bf v}_1 \times {\bf v}_2.$$
\begin{align*} {\bf v}_3 &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}\\ &= \begin{pmatrix} 1\cdot 4 - (-2)\cdot 4 \\ 4\cdot 4 - 1\cdot 4 \\ 1\cdot(-2) - 1\cdot 4 \end{pmatrix} \\ &= \begin{pmatrix} 12 \\ 12 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}
Since ${\bf v}_3$ is parallel to the normal vector of the triangle, the area of the triangle is half the magnitude of ${\bf v}_3$: $A = \tfrac12 \| {\bf v}_3\| = \tfrac12 \sqrt{12^2 + 12^2 + (-6)^2} = \boxed{6\sqrt{6}}$.
